	(33261,1160,'_title','field_60a22dc362739'),
	(33262,1160,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Uyghurs, Kazakhs and other predominantly Turkic Muslim peoples living in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region (XUAR) in China have long faced government-directed discrimination and persecution. In 2017, under the guise of a campaign to counter the ‘three evil forces’ of terrorism, extremism, and separatism, the government commenced a massive escalation of it abuses against these peoples. The campaign’s actual objectives are to eradicate Islamic religious beliefs and Turkic Muslim ethno-cultural practices, and to replace these with other secular, state-sanctioned, views and activities, and ultimately to ‘transform’ members of ethnic minorities in Xinjiang into obedient supporters of the Chinese Communist Party and President Xi Jinping.\r\n\r\nTo achieve this cultural erasure and political indoctrination, the government enacted far-reaching policies that violate the fundamental human rights and commenced a campaign of mass-arrest, mass-incarceration, and torture. More than a million men and women – Uyghurs, Kazakhs, Kyrgyz, Uzbeks, Tatars, Tajiks, and Dungans – have been arbitrarily arrested, denied due process, and unlawfully interned in so-called ‘re-education camps’ (that is, internment camps), where they were subjected to a ceaseless indoctrination campaign as well as physical and psychological torture and other forms of ill-treatment.'),
